Distance Measures for MPEG-7-based Retrieval 
content:
1 ABSTRACT :
1-1:In visual information retrieval the careful choice of suitable proximity measures is a crucial success factor .
1-2:The evaluation presented in this paper aims at showing that the distance measures suggested by the MPEG 7 group for the visual descriptors can be beaten by general purpose measures .
1-3:Eight visual MPEG 7 descriptors were selected and 38 distance measures implemented .
1-4:Three media collections were created and assessed, performance indicators developed and more than 22500 tests performed .
1-5:Additionally, a quantisation model was developed to be able to use predicate based distance measures on continuous data as well .
1-6:The evaluation shows that the distance measures recommended in the MPEG 7 standard are among the best but that other measures perform even better .
1-7:H.3.3 [Information Storage and Retrieval]: Information Search .
2 INTRODUCTION :
2-1:The MPEG 7 standard defines among others a set of descriptors for visual media .
2-2:Each descriptor consists of a feature extraction mechanism, a description (in binary and XML format) and guidelines that define how to apply the descriptor on different kinds of media (e.g .
2-3:on temporal media) .
2-4:The MPEG 7 descriptors have been carefully designed to meet partially complementaryrequirements of different application domains: archival, browsing, retrieval, etc .
2-5:[9] .
2-6:In the following, we will exclusively deal with the visual MPEG 7 descriptors in the context of media retrieval .
2-7:The visual MPEG 7 descriptors fall in five groups: colour, texture, shape, motion and others (e.g .
2-8:face description) and sum up to 16 basic descriptors .
2-9:For retrieval applications, a rule for each descriptor is mandatory that defines how to measure the similarity of two descriptions .
2-10:Common rules are distance functions, like the Euclidean distance and the Mahalanobis distance .
2-11:Unfortunately, the MPEG 7 standard does not include distance measures in the normative part, because it was not designed to be (and should not exclusively understood to be) retrieval specific .
2-12:However, the MPEG 7 authors give recommendations, which distance measure to use on a particular descriptor .
2-13:These recommendations are based on accurate knowledge of the descriptors' behaviour and the description structures .
2-14:In the present study a large number of successful distance measures from different areas (statistics, psychology, medicine, social and economic sciences, etc.) were implemented and applied on MPEG 7 data vectors to verify whether or not the recommended MPEG 7 distance measures are really the best for any reasonable class of media objects .
2-15:From the MPEG 7 tests and the recommendations it does not become clear, how many and which distance measures have been tested on the visual descriptors and the MPEG 7 test datasets .
2-16:The hypothesis is that analytically derived distance measures may be good in general but only a quantitative analysis is capable to identify the best distance measure for a specific feature extraction method .
2-17:The paper is organised as follows .
2-18:Section 2 gives a minimum of background information on the MPEG 7 descriptors and distance measurement in visual information retrieval (VIR, see [3], [16]) .
2-19:Section 3 gives an overview over the implemented distance measures .
2-20:Section 4 describes the test setup, including the test data and the implemented evaluation methods .
2-21:Finally, Section 5 presents the results per descriptor and over all descriptors. .
3 BACKGROUND :
3-1:2.1 MPEG 7: visual descriptors The visual part of the MPEG 7 standard defines several descriptors .
3-2:Not all of them are really descriptors in the sense that they extract properties from visual media .
3-3:Some of them are just structures for descriptor aggregation or localisation .
3-4:The basic descriptors are Color Layout, Color Structure, Dominant Color, Scalable Color, Edge Histogram, Homogeneous Texture, Texture Browsing, Region based Shape, Contour based Shape, Camera Motion, Parametric Motion and Motion Activity .
3-5:Other descriptors are based on low level descriptors or semantic information: Group of Frames Group of Pictures Color (based on Scalable Color), Shape 3D (based on 3D mesh information), Motion Trajectory (based on object segmentation) and Face Recognition (based on face extraction) .
3-6:Descriptors for spatiotemporal aggregation and localisation are: Spatial 2D Coordinates, Grid Layout, Region Locator (spatial), Time Series, Temporal Interpolation (temporal) and SpatioTemporal Locator (combined) .
3-7:Finally, other structures exist for colour spaces, colour quantisation and multiple 2D views of 3D objects .
3-8:These additional structures allow combining the basic descriptors in multiple ways and on different levels .
3-9:But they do not change the characteristics of the extracted information .
3-10:Consequently, structures for aggregation and localisation were not considered in the work described in this paper .
3-11:2.2 Similarity measurement on visual data Generally, similarity measurement on visual information aims at imitating human visual similarity perception .
3-12:Unfortunately, human perception is much more complex than any of the existing similarity models (it includes perception, recognition and subjectivity) .
3-13:The common approach in visual information retrieval is measuring dis similarity as distance .
3-14:Both, query object and candidate object are represented by their corresponding feature vectors .
3-15:The distance between these objects is measured by computing the distance between the two vectors .
3-16:Consequently, the process is independent of the employed querying paradigm (e.g .
3-17:query by example) .
3-18:The query object may be natural (e.g .
3-19:a real object) or artificial (e.g .
3-20:properties of a group of objects) .
3-21:Goal of the measurement process is to express a relationship between the two objects by their distance .
3-22:Iteration for multiple candidates allows then to define a partial order over the candidates and to address those in a (to be defined) neighbourhood being similar to the query object .
3-23:At this point, it has to be mentioned that in a multi descriptor environmentespecially in MPEG 7 we are only half way towards a statement on similarity .
3-24:If multiple descriptors are used (e.g .
3-25:a descriptor scheme), a rule has to be defined how to combine all distances to a global value for each object .
3-26:Still, distance measurement is the most important first step in similarity measurement .
3-27:Obviously, the main task of good distance measures is to reorganise descriptor space in a way that media objects with the highest similarity are nearest to the query object .
3-28:If distance is defined minimal, the query object is always in the origin of distance space and similar candidates should form clusters around the origin that are as large as possible .
3-29:Consequently, many well known distance measures are based on geometric assumptions of descriptor space (e.g .
3-30:Euclidean distance is based on the metric axioms) .
3-31:Unfortunately, these measures do not fit ideally with human similarity perception (e.g .
3-32:due to human subjectivity) .
3-33:To overcome this shortage, researchers from different areas have developed alternative models that are mostly predicate based (descriptors are assumed to contain just binary elements, e.g .
3-34:Tversky's Feature Contrast Model [17]) and fit better with human perception .
3-35:In the following distance measures of both groups of approaches will be considered. .
4 DISTANCE MEASURES :
4-1:The distance measures used in this work have been collected from various areas (Subsection 3.1) .
4-2:Because they work on differently quantised data, Subsection 3.2 sketches a model for unification on the basis of quantitative descriptions .
4-3:Finally, Subsection 3.3 introduces the distance measures as well as their origin and the idea they implement .
4-4:3.1 Sources Distance measurement is used in many research areas such as psychology, sociology (e.g .
4-5:comparing test results), medicine (e.g .
4-6:comparing parameters of test persons), economics (e.g .
4-7:comparing balance sheet ratios), etc .
4-8:Naturally, the character of data available in these areas differs significantly .
4-9:Essentially, there are two extreme cases of data vectors (and distance measures): predicatebased (all vector elements are binary, e.g .
4-10:{0, 1}) and quantitative (all vector elements are continuous, e.g .
4-11:[0, 1]) .
4-12:Predicates express the existence of properties and represent highlevel information while quantitative values can be used to measure and mostly represent low level information .
4-13:Predicates are often employed in psychology, sociology and other human related sciences and most predicate based distance measures were therefore developed in these areas .
4-14:Descriptions in visual information retrieval are nearly ever (if they do not integrate semantic information) quantitative .
4-15:Consequently, mostly quantitative distance measures are used in visual information retrieval .
4-16:The goal of this work is to compare the MPEG 7 distance measures with the most powerful distance measures developed in other areas .
4-17:Since MPEG 7 descriptions are purely quantitative but some of the most sophisticated distance measures are defined exclusively on predicates, a model is mandatory that allows the application of predicate based distance measures on quantitative data .
4-18:The model developed for this purpose is presented in the next section .
4-19:3.2 Quantisation model The goal of the quantisation model is to redefine the set operators that are usually used in predicate based distance measures on continuous data .
4-20:The first in visual information retrieval to follow this approach were Santini and Jain, who tried to apply Tversky's Feature Contrast Model [17] to content based image retrieval [12], [13] .
4-21:They interpreted continuous data as fuzzy predicates and used fuzzy set operators .
4-22:Unfortunately, their model suffered from several shortcomings they described in [12], [13] (for example, the quantitative model worked only for one specific version of the original predicate based measure) .
4-23:The main idea of the presented quantisation model is that set operators are replaced by statistical functions .
4-24:In [5] the authors could show that this interpretation of set operators is reasonable .
4-25:The model offers a solution for the descriptors considered in the evaluation .
4-26:It is not specific to one distance measure, but can be applied to any predicate based measure .
4-27:Below, it will be shown that the model does not only work for predicate data but for quantitative data as well .
4-28:Each measure implementing the model can be used as a substitute for the original predicate based measure .
4-29:Generally, binary properties of two objects (e.g .
4-30:media objects) can exist in both objects (denoted as a), in just one (b, c) or in none of them (d) .
4-31:The operator needed for these relationships are UNION, MINUS and NOT .
4-32:In the quantisation model they are replaced as follows (see [5] for further details) .
