7-16:A Manhattan metric was used to measure proximity (see [6] for details) .
7-17:Descriptor extraction was performed using the MPEG 7 reference implementation .
7-18:In the extraction process each descriptor was applied on the entire content of each media object and the following extraction parameters were used .
7-19:Colour in Color Structure was quantised to 32 bins .
7-20:For Dominant Color colour space was set to YCrCb, 5 bit default quantisation was used and the default value for spatial coherency was used .
7-21:Homogeneous Texture was quantised to 32 components .
7-22:Scalable Color values were quantised to sizeof(int) 3 bits and 64 bins were used .
7-23:Finally, Texture Browsing was used with five components .
7-24:These descriptors were applied on three media collections with image content: the Brodatz dataset (112 images, 512x512 pixel), a subset of the Corel dataset (260 images, 460x300 pixel, portrait and landscape) and a dataset with coats of arms images (426 images, 200x200 pixel) .
7-25:Figure 1 shows examples from the three collections .
7-26:Designing appropriate test sets for a visual evaluation is a highly difficult task (for example, see the TREC video 2002 report [15]) .
7-27:Of course, for identifying the best distance measure for a descriptor, it should be tested on an infinite number of media objects .
7-28:But this is not the aim of this study .
7-29:It is just evaluated if for likely image collections better proximity measures than those suggested by the MPEG 7 group can be found .
7-30:Collections of this relatively small size were used in the evaluation, because the applied evaluation methods are above a certain minimum size invariant against collection size and for smaller collections it is easier to define a high quality ground truth .
7-31:Still, the average ratio of ground truth size to collection size is at least 1:7 .
7-32:Especially, no collection from the MPEG 7 dataset was used in the evaluation because the evaluations should show, how well the descriptors and the recommended distance measures perform on "unknown" material .
7-33:When the descriptor extraction was finished, the resulting XML descriptions were transformed into a data matrix with 798 lines (media objects) and 314 columns (descriptor elements) .
7-34:To be usable with distance measures that do not integrate domain knowledge, the elements of this data matrix were normalised to [0, 1] .
7-35:For the distance evaluation next to the normalised data matrixhuman similarity judgement is needed .
7-36:In this work, the ground truth is built of twelve groups of similar images (four for each dataset) .
7-37:Group membership was rated by humans based on semantic criterions .
7-38:Table 4 summarises the twelve groups and the underlying descriptions .
7-39:It has to be noticed, that some of these groups (especially 5, 7 and 10) are much harder to find with lowlevel descriptors than others .
7-40:4.2 Evaluation method Usually, retrieval evaluation is performed based on a ground truth with recall and precision (see, for example, [3], [16]) .
7-41:In multidescriptor environments this leads to a problem, because the resulting recall and precision values are strongly influenced by the method used to merge the distance values for one media object .
7-42:Even though it is nearly impossible to say, how big the influence of a single distance measure was on the resulting recall and precision values, this problem has been almost ignored so far .
7-43:In Subsection 2.2 it was stated that the major task of a distance measure is to bring the relevant media objects as close to the origin (where the query object lies) as possible .
7-44:Even in a multidescriptor environment it is then simple to identify the similar objects in a large distance space .
